Next, we briefly comment on the efficiency of the engine cycle. The cycle couples optical states of the ion (the working fluid) with its vibrational states (the load). As discussed previously, in a generic scenario it is not straightforward to differentiate heat from work and hence the usual definition of efficiency does not apply. Since the energy of each photon quantum is much greater than a phonon quantum, it is also not particularly useful to define the efficiency purely in terms of energy conversion. However, this set-up still converts photon quanta (in the engine) to phonon quanta (in the load). Therefore, analogous to solar cells, we define an efficiency of conversion of quanta, ηQ, as the net increase in the mean phonon number in the load divided by the total input of photon quanta in the working fluid throughout the various strokes. For the cycle with pDA=0.32\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
